    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>House Smoking Ban</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Barry R Bloom, dean of Harvard School of Public Health, says House of Representatives' ban on smoking sends message that smoking is unacceptable</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''House Bans Smoking, and Few Complain'' (news article, Jan. 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''House Bans Smoking, and Few Complain'' (news article, Jan. 11):</p>
        <p>The new leadership's ban on smoking inside the House of Representatives was more than a symbolic gesture indicating that ''the days of smoke-filled rooms in the Capitol are over.''</p>
        <p>It was also a concrete action strengthening one of the most important tools recognized by public health to prevent addiction to tobacco -- and that is to make smoking socially unacceptable.</p>
        <p>Smoking is the largest preventable cause of premature death in the United States (responsible for 1 of every 5 deaths), killing some 438,000 Americans annually. With help from Congress, we can end the days of smoke-filled rooms everywhere in America.</p>
        <p>Barry R. Bloom  Boston, Jan. 11, 2007</p>
        <p>The writer is dean of the Harvard School of Public Health.</p>
      </block>
